{{Infobox university |image=<!-- Do NOT place a non-free image here without complying with WP:NFCC #10c --> |motto= ''Discover. Innovate. Lead.'' |name=UW-Milwaukee College of Engineering and Applied Science |type = [[Public university|Public]] |established = |dean = Michael R. Lovell |city =[[Milwaukee]] |state =[[Wisconsin]] |country =[[United States]] |campus =[[University of WisconsinâMilwaukee]] |phone= |website= [http://www.uwm.edu/CEAS http://www.uwm.edu/CEAS] |logo=<center>[[Image:UW-Milwaukee.png|150px]]</center> |}} The '''College of Engineering and Applied Science''' is a college within the '''[[University of WisconsinâMilwaukee]]'''. It offers bachelor, master and doctoral degrees in [[civil engineering]], [[electrical engineering]], [[industrial engineering]], [[materials engineering]], [[mechanical engineering]], and [[computer science]].
Based on the statistical analysis by H.J. Newton, Professor of Statistics at Texas A&M University in 1997 on the [[United States National Research Council|National Research Council]] report issued in 1995, the school was ranked 73rd nationally in the [[United States National Research Council rankings|National Research Council]] (NRC) rankings,<ref>[http://www.stat.tamu.edu/~jnewton/nrc_rankings/nrc1.html#RANKBYAREA A Brief Summary of the NRC Rankings], Texas A&M University</ref> with its [[Civil Engineering]] program 69th,<ref>[http://www.stat.tamu.edu/~jnewton/nrc_rankings/nrc41.html#area22 NRC Rankings in each of the 41 Areas:] civil engineering, Texas A&M University</ref> [[Electronic Engineering]] 96th,<ref>[http://www.stat.tamu.edu/~jnewton/nrc_rankings/nrc41.html#area23 NRC Rankings in each of the 41 Areas:] Electronic Engineering, Texas A&M University</ref> [[Industrial Engineering]] 34th,<ref>[http://www.stat.tamu.edu/~jnewton/nrc_rankings/nrc41.html#area24 NRC Rankings in each of the 41 Areas:] Industrial Engineering, Texas A&M University</ref> [[Materials science]] 60th,<ref>[http://www.stat.tamu.edu/~jnewton/nrc_rankings/nrc41.html#area25 NRC Rankings in each of the 41 Areas:] Materials science, Texas A&M University</ref> and [[Mechanical Engineering]] 87th.<ref>[http://www.stat.tamu.edu/~jnewton/nrc_rankings/nrc41.html#area26 NRC Rankings in each of the 41 Areas:] Mechanical Engineering, Texas A&M University</ref>The school ranks 129th nationally by ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'', <ref name="Best Engineering Schools">[http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-engineering-schools/eng-rankings/page+6 Best Engineering Schools],''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''.</ref> with its [[computer science]] program ranked 110th in 2011.<ref name="Rankings: Computer Science">[http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-science-schools/computer-science-rankings/page+5 Rankings: Computer Science], ''[[US News & World Report]]'', 2010.</ref>
